      "arraySize": 1,
      "dimensions": 1,
      "description": "keepshape - This parameter determines the precision of a linear skin (case c in the diagram). If enabled, it ensures that the generated surface goes through each cross-section. Here, a cross-section can be a face or a surface boundary, depending on the types being skinned. If disabled, Preserve Shape produces a surface whose CVs coincide with the CVs of the cross-sections (after they have being converted to a common type and an identical number of CVs). The skinning algorithm is faster with shape preservation OFF, but it lacks precision.\t\nSkinning with shape preservation ON may produce unintuitive shapes when the cross-sections have many coincident CVs or are very close to each other. In this case try to jitter the CVs, vary the V Order (see below), or simply disable shape preservation.\t\t\nPreserve shape is deactivated when doing bi-linear skinning.",
      "tooltip": "",
      "help": "",
      "units": "",
      "examples": [],
